<div id="review_3904017549" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3904017549" />
    <a title="Joe Comeford" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/132280871-joe-comeford"><img alt="Joe Comeford" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3904017549?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Joe Comeford" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Joe Comeford" href="/user/show/132280871-joe-comeford">Joe Comeford</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780976075707" href="/book/show/48711623-slow-brewing-tea">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3904017549" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15025218304210745462">I couldn’t put the book down. Extremely well written that leaves you wanting more. The book is fascinating in many respects. It’s a love story with an American GI at Misawa AB in search of God in northern eastern Japan in 1978. It’s a love story with a beautiful Japanese lady named Nori which takes many turns and the friendships that develop over a forty year period of time.<br/><br/>It’s a Christian based book from an “unbeliever” point of view, Isiah searches to find God and what’s in store for him duri</span>
  <span id="freeText15025218304210745462" style="display:none">I couldn’t put the book down. Extremely well written that leaves you wanting more. The book is fascinating in many respects. It’s a love story with an American GI at Misawa AB in search of God in northern eastern Japan in 1978. It’s a love story with a beautiful Japanese lady named Nori which takes many turns and the friendships that develop over a forty year period of time.<br /><br />It’s a Christian based book from an “unbeliever” point of view, Isiah searches to find God and what’s in store for him during his journey to find God, with the “tools” learned such as “The Three Treasures “ from Taoism perspective. It left me, a Christian with self inflection with new questions and my personal relationship with God. After reading the book, it makes you wonder why more Japanese are not Christians. It’s estimated that only 1% of the Japanese people are Christian, in contrast to crossing over from traditional Shintoism, Taoism, Japanese Confucianism, and Buddhism. I was sad when the book ended. Will touch your heart.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15025218304210745462" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


